        "timestamp": "2018-04-19 15:29:04.000000000",
        "message": "Abandoned\n\nClosing might interfere with fetch, so just leaving it as is.  Sonar fixes will be made with another JIRA.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "f96db0cc6b59441427fa3668236791531dc95309",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-04-19 15:34:37.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJim, I think we need to do something about it.   As it stands right now, I think there may be a leak of unclosed consumers when the setFilter is invoked.  One solution could be to pass the filter in the constructor, another one that does not require passing it in the constructor, is to delay building the consumer until the first fetch.   I think we should open a ticket to track this, I think there's a resource leak.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "2cfdc7d56905a4a5f3fbbb934a7e333d8490418a",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-04-19 15:36:38.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> Jim, I think we need to do something about it.   As it stands right\n > now, I think there may be a leak of unclosed consumers when the\n > setFilter is invoked.  One solution could be to pass the filter in\n > the constructor, another one that does not require passing it in\n > the constructor, is to delay building the consumer until the first\n > fetch.   I think we should open a ticket to track this, I think\n > there's a resource leak.\n\nAs you pointed out, \"close()\" doesn't do anything, so there is no leak.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "bc19e2f831b6e88b46255d3f0e162b4fd306a71a",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-04-19 16:25:32.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> (1 comment)\n > \n > > Jim, I think we need to do something about it.   As it stands\n > right\n > > now, I think there may be a leak of unclosed consumers when the\n > > setFilter is invoked.  One solution could be to pass the filter\n > in\n > > the constructor, another one that does not require passing it in\n > > the constructor, is to delay building the consumer until the\n > first\n > > fetch.   I think we should open a ticket to track this, I think\n > > there's a resource leak.\n > \n > As you pointed out, \"close()\" doesn't do anything, so there is no\n > leak.\n\nIf you'd prefer, I can close the old consumer in a way that won't interfere with fetch.  However, that will require changes in a number of places within this class.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
